## I Introduction

Continuous-wave (CW) distributed feedback (DFB) quantum cascade lasers (QCLs) are especially attractive coherent single-mode light sources in the mid-infrared regime [1]. For various applications, such as trace gas sensing, free-space communications and pollution monitoring, high-performance surface emission allowing for a low beam divergence is highly desirable [2, 3, 4]. Since the light generated in QCL is transverse-magnetic (TM) polarized, conventional vertical cavity surface-emitting structure is not feasible in this configuration. Consequently, a popular way to realize surface emission is by the use of a second-order Bragg grating for feedback and outcoupling. The surface-emitting DFB QCLs operating in continuous wave (CW) at room temperature have already been demonstrated, but these lasers require a buried second-order grating and therefore an epitaxial growth after the grating fabrication on InGaAs confining layer of the QCL active region is needed [5, 6]. An alternative to this sophisticated and expensive approach is to make use of the surface waves of a grating etched in the top highly doped waveguide layer [7, 8, 9]. However, the introduction of a metal in the grating groove usually will result in a high metal absorption loss. Especially, the second-order grating designed by _A. Lyakh et al._ was fabricated in a thin cladding layer [10]. As a result, this type of surface-emitting QCL suffers from a much larger waveguide loss comparing to their Fabry-Perot (FP) counterparts. Recently, _C. Sigler et al._ designed a surface-emitting top grating-coupled DFB QCL allowing for single mode lasing at low threshold current and high slope efficiency, which was predicted with the potential for watt-range CW power emission [11]. However, no further progress on the structure is achieved. More recently, _P. Jouy et al._ presented a surface emitting laser array design based on distributed Bragg reflectors together with a second-order top grating DFB extractor for low optical losses and efficient heat dissipation [12]. Yet the realization of CW operation at room temperature for such top grating surface-emitting structure is still an unsolved problem owing to the fabrication imperfections. Up to now, top grating surface emission was obtained in pulsed mode only. Encouraging by the index-coupled top grating design by _M. Carras et al._[13], we optimize the second-order metal/semiconductor surface grating design by incorporating the DFB structure on a thicker waveguide, along with the control of an appropriate grating duty cycle, to achieve a low loss coupling mechanism with a proper coupling strength.

In this letter, single-mode CW emission via the substrate at room temperature was demonstrated for a 4.8 \(\mu\)m top grating laser. For a 13-\(\mu\)m-wide and 4-mm-long laser, CW output power of 94 mW was obtained at 25 \({}^{\circ}\)C with a low threshold current density of 1.21 kA/cm\({}^{2}\). A far-field radiation pattern with a low divergence angle of \(0.58^{\circ}\times 16.2^{\circ}\) is obtained. Reliable single-mode emission with a side-mode suppression ratio (SMSR) about 30 dB was achieved from 10 \({}^{\circ}\)C to 40 \({}^{\circ}\)C.

## II Device Design and Fabrication

The QCL structure described in this letter was grown by solid-source molecular beam epitaxy on an n-InP (Si, \(2\times 10^{17}\) cm\({}^{-3}\)) substrate based on a double-phonon resonant design. The active region of each laser structure consists of 35 superlattice periods, which are alternating strain-compensated In\({}_{0.669}\)Ga\({}_{0.331}\)As/In\({}_{0.362}\)Al\({}_{0.638}\)As quantum well and barrier layers. The layer sequence and thickness are identical to that in Ref. [14]. The entire structure was as follows: 1.34 \(\mu\)m lower InP cladding layer (Si, \(1.5\times 10^{17}\) cm\({}^{-3}\)),0.3 \(\mu\)m-thick In\({}_{0.53}\)Ga\({}_{0.47}\)As layer (Si, 4 \(\times\) 10\({}^{16}\) cm\({}^{-3}\)), 1.764 \(\mu\)m active core, 0.3 \(\mu\)m-thick In\({}_{0.53}\)Ga\({}_{0.47}\)As layer (Si, 4 \(\times\) 10\({}^{16}\) cm\({}^{-3}\)), 2.6 \(\mu\)m upper InP cladding layer (Si, 3 \(\times\) 10\({}^{16}\) cm\({}^{-3}\)), 0.15 \(\mu\)m gradually doped InP contact layer (Si, 1 \(\times\) 10\({}^{17}\) cm\({}^{-3}\) to 3 \(\times\) 10\({}^{17}\) cm\({}^{-3}\)), and finally a highly doped InP contact layer (Si, 5 \(\times\) 10\({}^{18}\) cm\({}^{-3}\)) as the host layer for the grating.

According to the coupled-wave theory for gratings [15], the feedback in the DFB structure relies on periodic modulation of refractive index. For a second order grating, first-order diffraction perpendicular to the plane contributes to surface emission and second-order diffraction parallel to the plane provides feedback. Here we simulated the second-order surface grating structure with different cap layer thickness and grating duty cycle \(\sigma\) (defined by the ratio of grating teeth and period) based on finite-element method with periodical boundary condition to find the optimal grating design. The material properties of active region and waveguide are taken into account in term of complex refractive index\({}_{x}\) Fig. 1 (a) shows the modal loss as a function the cap layer thickness. For the second uniform grating, the coupling coefficient is proportional to the Fourier components \(\varepsilon=\sin(\sigma 2\pi)\), which implies a larger coupling coefficient when \(\sigma=25\%\). The two DFB modes illustrated in the inset of Fig. 1 (a), denoted as mode 1 and mode 2, correspond to the asymmetric mode and symmetric mode respectively. The calculation result reveals the value of modal loss for mode 1 is always smaller than that for mode 2. Consequently, the asymmetric mode is always the lasing mode for lower threshold gain. Besides, the largest loss gap between the two modes appears when the cap layer thickness denotes 0.4 \(\mu\)m, which contributes to the stability of emission of the low loss mode. For a fixed cap layer thickness of 0.4 \(\mu\)m and a grating depth of 190 nm, Fig. 1 (b) shows the coupling coefficient \(\kappa\) as the grating duty cycle changes, and the inset shows the scanning electron microscope (SEM) image of the grating structure.

Given the duty cycle \(\sigma=25\%\), we obtained a coupling coefficient \(\kappa=4.4\) cm\({}^{-1}\). For 4-mm-long cavities, a moderate coupling strength \(\kappa\)L of \(\sim\)1.76 is deduced, which is appropriate for an efficient surface emission. Based on the results of the simulation, a 0.4 \(\upmu\)m-thick highly doped layer was grown, and the second-order grating with a period of \(\Lambda=1.5\)\(\mu\)m and duty cycle \(\sigma=25\%\) (purposed at 15% \(\sim\) 35%) was defined using holographic lithography technique and transferred by wet chemical etching to the depth of about 190 nm.

After the fabrication of the second-order grating on the top highly doping layer, the wafer was etched into double channel waveguide laser with an average core width of 13 \(\mu\)m by conventional photolithography and non-selective chemical etching. A 450 nm-thick SiO\({}_{2}\) insulating layer was deposited by Chemical Vapor Deposition (CVD) around the ridges. After evaporation of the top non-alloyed Ti/Au contacts, an additional 5-\(\mu\)m-thick gold layer was electroplated subsequently around the laser ridges to further improve heat dissipation. After being thinned down to about 120 \(\mu\)m, a Ge/Au/Ni/Au metal contact layer was deposited on the substrate side of the wafer. For surface emission from the substrate, a 150 \(\mu\)m-wide window was left on the substrate contact layer by metal lift-off. Finally, the waveguides were cleaved into 4-mm-long bars. The HR coating, consisting of Al\({}_{2}\)O\({}_{3}\)/Ti/Au/Al\({}_{2}\)O\({}_{3}\) (200/10/100/120 nm), was deposited on the back facet by e-beam evaporation.

## III Device Characterization

The devices were mounted epilayer side down on SiC heat sinks with indium solder for effective heat dissipation and wire bonded to an external contact pad. Then the heat sink was mounted on a holder containing a thermoelectric cooler (TEC) and a thermistor to regulate and monitor the temperature. The emitted optical power was measured with a calibrated thermopile detector placed right in front of the laser facet without any correction. The measurement of lasing spectra was performed with a Fourier transform infrared (FTIR) spectrometer with a resolution of 0.25 cm\({}^{-1}\) in rapid scan mode. Far-field characterization was performed by placing the laser on a stepped motor control rotational stage with a resolution of 0.05\({}^{\circ}\) in cavity-length direction and 0.5\({}^{\circ}\) in ridge-width direction. A nitrogen-cooled HgCdTe detector was located 30 cm away to collect the lasing light.

