Fig. 2 shows the typical CW light-current-voltage (L-I-V) curve of the 13-\(\mu\)m-wide and 4-mm-long laser at different heat sink temperatures from 20 to 40 \({}^{\circ}\)C. For temperature characteristics of the DFB QCL, CW output power was observed to decrease from 101 to 40 mW, while the threshold current density increased from 1.15 kA/cm\({}^{2}\) to 1.35 kA/cm\({}^{2}\) at heat sink temperatures of 20 and 40 \({}^{\circ}\)C. This high surface emission performance is attributed to the thicker and low loss waveguide used in this structure. The CW output power of 94 mW from the substrate facet was obtained at 25 \({}^{\circ}\)C, with a low threshold current density of 1.21 kA/cm\({}^{2}\). In contrast, the edge-emitting output power of the same device was also measured in Fig. 2. The CW output power of 356 mW was obtained at 20 \({}^{\circ}\)C. For the n-InP doped substrate thickness of 120 \(\mu\)m and doping level of \(2\times 10^{17}\) cm\({}^{-3}\), the optical transmission at the substrate-air interface for this lasing wavelength is about 30%. The ratio between surface emission and edge emission is derived to be about 0.95 for this device, which indicates a comparative extraction efficiency of substrate direction. Nevertheless, an existing anti-reflective coating on the substrate facet will result to 25% increase in the output power. Besides, the optical power and outcoupling efficiency for the surface emission can be further increased by optimizing the waveguide design [11, 12], which is worthy of future study.

Fig. 3 shows the CW surface emission spectra of the second-order top grating DFB QCL at different heat sink temperatures from 10 \({}^{\circ}\)C to 40 \({}^{\circ}\)C. A single-mode emission is observed among the entire investigated temperature range with a SMSR about 30 dB at injection currents of 1.1 Ith. As is shown in the upper inset of Fig. 4, the peak emission spectrum was observed to shift from 2068.3 cm\({}^{-1}\) at 10 \({}^{\circ}\)C to 2057.1 cm\({}^{-1}\) at 40 \({}^{\circ}\)C, corresponding to a temperature tuning coefficient \(\Delta v/\Delta\mathrm{T}=-0.374\) cm\({}^{-1}\cdot\mathrm{K}^{-1}\). The lower inset shows the lasing spectra of the same device at different injection currents in CW operation at 20 \({}^{\circ}\)C. As the driving current increases from 0.7 A to 0.9 A with a step of 0.5 A, the peak emission spectrum shifts from 2065.4 cm\({}^{-1}\) to 2063.2 cm\({}^{-1}\). A current tunability of \(-10.75\) cm\({}^{-1}\cdot\mathrm{A}^{-1}\) was obtained. Stable single-longitudinal-mode operation to relatively high driving currents and over a wide range of heat sink temperatures is expected, because second-order DFB lasers are inherently complex-coupled devices for which the mode of least radiation loss is the one favored to lase. The present of loss-coupling component, combining with the dominating index-coupling scheme, would prevent the device radiation from oscillation at both edges of the stop-band [16].

